                    "id": "photon_energy_wavelength_sweep_full_spectrum",
                    "description": "Sweep λ from 10 nm (extreme UV / soft X-ray) to 1 mm (microwave / CMB peak) across 5 orders of magnitude on a log scale, plotting both ν(λ) and Δε(λ) — the canonical photon-energy curves spanning the atmospheric-radiation regime from soft X-ray (~120 eV) through UV-C (~12 eV), UV-B (~4 eV), visible (~2 eV at 500 nm), near-IR (~1 eV at 1 μm), thermal-IR (~0.1 eV at 10 μm), down to microwave (~1 meV at 1 mm). Both ν = c/λ and Δε = hc/λ scale strictly as 1/λ — on a log-log plot, ν vs λ is a straight line of slope -1 (intercept log(c) ≈ 8.48), and Δε vs λ is a straight line of slope -1 (intercept log(hc) ≈ -25.3). Anchors the design observation that hotter sources emit higher-energy photons (UV/X-ray) while colder sources emit lower-energy photons (IR/microwave) — the Wien-displacement relationship between source temperature and per-photon energy.",
