                    "id": "photon_energy_uv_photolysis_band_sweep",
                    "description": "Sweep λ across the UV-photolysis band 180-400 nm (the wavelength range driving atmospheric photodissociation reactions) at fine resolution, surfacing the per-photon energy variation across the canonical Chapman-cycle / NOx-photolysis range. At λ=180 nm (Schumann-Runge band for O2 photolysis, see chapman.esm), Δε ≈ 1.10e-18 J ≈ 6.9 eV; at λ=242 nm (canonical O2 + hν → 2 O photolysis), Δε ≈ 8.21e-19 J ≈ 5.1 eV; at λ=310 nm (canonical O3 + hν → O + O2 photolysis), Δε ≈ 6.41e-19 J ≈ 4.0 eV; at λ=400 nm (NO2 photolysis cutoff), Δε ≈ 4.97e-19 J ≈ 3.1 eV. The variation across the UV band drives the wavelength-dependent photolysis-rate coefficient j(λ) that maps actinic flux to photodissociation rate (j = ∫ σ(λ) · Φ(λ) · F(λ) dλ where σ is the absorption cross-section, Φ is the quantum yield, and F is the actinic flux per photon). Anchors the UV-band radiative-transfer application driving stratospheric ozone chemistry (S&P Ch. 5).",
